Why can‚Äôt I open my height map in map editor? It says it isn‚Äôt a right file, and crashes after I tried to import it
Melon 1/2/2025 3:39 PM
your heightmap needs to be 8/16 bit grayscale the same size as the original. Or to follow this tutorial for custom size https://ck3.paradoxwikis.com/Map_modding#Creating_a_Map_with_a_Custom_Resolution I think you also need to have indirection_heightmap and packed_heightmap files in the folder but not sure. You can copy them from the game.

Miria | Runeterra 1/17/2025 5:02 AM
my experience with the river map crashing is it's connected pixels that shouldnt be connected.
Each river pixel must be orthogonally adjacent to no more than 2 other river pixels, and splits and joins must be adjacent to no more than 3 other river pixels. Two-pixel wide rivers and rivers connected using only diagonal pixels will fail to render
 (edited)

KeizerHarm | T4N 1/19/2025 10:56 AM
Hey @cleembus ! Before you start modding with a map replacement, read this warning
10:57 AM
!tcmodding
YAGPDB.xyz BOT 1/19/2025 10:57 AM
Do you want to make a total conversion? Are you excited with an idea for a world, that you want to realise in CK3? And do you want to embark on that project with little prior modding experience? Consider these uncomfortable truths:
  • Total conversions are a terrifying chore to make. To get one going takes months of effort with little return on investment, and countless times where you're scratching your head at an inane vanilla system and spend a day in frustration before you figure it out. In that process, because you are figuring everything out, setbacks will happen again and again.
  • Total conversions are a big effort to maintain. If you've managed to finish one, after every big patch you will be redoing 10% of your mod again. Two or three times a year, you need to spend a few weeks on more dumb chores just to get the thing going as well as it did before the patch. And CK3 likely won't stop getting patches until the 2030s.
  • Total conversions do exist but they are, as a rule, made and maintained by teams. There are no TC mods in recent memory that have been made from scratch by a single person, and trust us, you don't want to be the first.
  • About every other week someone comes to the Coop with a vision for a world, and they ask for help making a map. They don't know what they are getting into, they burn themselves out and stop modding altogether.
Please, for your health and ours, consider very carefully whether you really want to do such a gigantic and thankless task as one of your first projects. CK3 is not a game engine, it is a game, and the larger the scope of your mod the bigger the pain.
KeizerHarm | T4N
Hey @cleembus ! Before you start modding with a map replacement, read this warning

YAGPDB.xyz BOT 1/21/2025 3:59 AM
Don't ask for a person to help, ask for the solution to your problem. Keep in mind we're all hobbyists, not people you can recruit for a time period. Be specific right off the bat. Don't wait for someone to acknowledge you, put all the information we need in your initial question. You're more likely to get an answer if you give us the ability to answer it without first asking more questions to clarify. Don't just tell what's going wrong, tell what you've already done. Is the error log clean? Have you isolated the issue to the smallest component? If you're looking for advice on an approach, have you looked at existing vanilla systems and found how they don't fulfill your needs?

New issues

  • set_color_from_title sets wrong colors if the title color has too high or low values for rgb use between 6 and 249, eg { 6 6 6 } for hsv use between 0.03 and 0.97, eg hsv{ 0.03 0.03 0.03 } otherwise the randomizing effect blows past the limits and breaks it

YAGPDB.xyz BOT 2/4/2025 9:43 PM
Do you want to make a total conversion? Are you excited with an idea for a world, that you want to realise in CK3? And do you want to embark on that project with little prior modding experience? Consider these uncomfortable truths:
  • Total conversions are a terrifying chore to make. To get one going takes months of effort with little return on investment, and countless times where you're scratching your head at an inane vanilla system and spend a day in frustration before you figure it out. In that process, because you are figuring everything out, setbacks will happen again and again.
  • Total conversions are a big effort to maintain. If you've managed to finish one, after every big patch you will be redoing 10% of your mod again. Two or three times a year, you need to spend a few weeks on more dumb chores just to get the thing going as well as it did before the patch. And CK3 likely won't stop getting patches until the 2030s.
  • Total conversions do exist but they are, as a rule, made and maintained by teams. There are no TC mods in recent memory that have been made from scratch by a single person, and trust us, you don't want to be the first.
  • About every other week someone comes to the Coop with a vision for a world, and they ask for help making a map. They don't know what they are getting into, they burn themselves out and stop modding altogether.
Please, for your health and ours, consider very carefully whether you really want to do such a gigantic and thankless task as one of your first projects. CK3 is not a game engine, it is a game, and the larger the scope of your mod the bigger the pain.

Wlqos (Vasikle) | HAEGEMONIA 2/21/2025 3:34 PM
Does anybody have experience with using GIS for making maps in CK3 ?
Natalie
Or to put it more precisely; when making a map, how many miles does one pixel equate to? Is that even how travel is calculated by CK3? (edited)
BOMBUS_FRIGIDUS | TWR 2/21/2025 8:17 PM
CK3's map distorts distances, so if you were to measure pixels-to-miles along different vectors on the map, you'd find different results. For a rough measure from London to Paris, there are 0.71 miles/pixel (1.14 kilometers/pixel). Emphasis on "rough." As in HDTin's answer, travel speed is pretty arbitrary, which is nice for performance but a shame for geographic interest.
Wlqos (Vasikle) | HAEGEMONIA
Does anybody have experience with using GIS for making maps in CK3 ?
BOMBUS_FRIGIDUS | TWR 2/21/2025 8:17 PM
Yep, feel free to DM a more involved question. FWIW I've mostly found that CK3 maps need to be lovingly hand-crafted.

YAGPDB.xyz BOT 3/3/2025 5:53 PM
Do you want to make a total conversion? Are you excited with an idea for a world, that you want to realise in CK3? And do you want to embark on that project with little prior modding experience? Consider these uncomfortable truths:
  • Total conversions are a terrifying chore to make. To get one going takes months of effort with little return on investment, and countless times where you're scratching your head at an inane vanilla system and spend a day in frustration before you figure it out. In that process, because you are figuring everything out, setbacks will happen again and again.
  • Total conversions are a big effort to maintain. If you've managed to finish one, after every big patch you will be redoing 10% of your mod again. Two or three times a year, you need to spend a few weeks on more dumb chores just to get the thing going as well as it did before the patch. And CK3 likely won't stop getting patches until the 2030s.
  • Total conversions do exist but they are, as a rule, made and maintained by teams. There are no TC mods in recent memory that have been made from scratch by a single person, and trust us, you don't want to be the first.
  • About every other week someone comes to the Coop with a vision for a world, and they ask for help making a map. They don't know what they are getting into, they burn themselves out and stop modding altogether.
Please, for your health and ours, consider very carefully whether you really want to do such a gigantic and thankless task as one of your first projects. CK3 is not a game engine, it is a game, and the larger the scope of your mod the bigger the pain.

Quan 3/5/2025 5:22 AM
Making a map is making a total conversion mod unfortunately. All mods changing the map have to change most of vanilla otherwise you get error logs 50000+ errors long. I'm making a total conversion mod with a small team, and we've been at it for a few months now, it takes forever because of the amount of stuff you have to change (A playtester found Genghis khan wasn't removed properly, and travelled through time and space to attack Paradis!). To make a map you need: 1) to remove any vanilla files that relate to the base game map, every decision, every event, every script. 2) To create your own high quality heightmap 3) To hand drawn thousands of individual baronies, sort them into titles and define them properly 4) To paint the map and make it look good. 5) Add rivers and other detailing, such as terrain types 6) Create a full history for your entire world, with each of the individual baronies needing to know when any building is built on it, over the course of centuries. 7) Make every county, kingdom and empire owned by a character you made the dna, traits and modifiers for. Its a lot tbh
Splendid
AOT takes place in Madagascar?

Yep, aot's map is just the real world map flipped and mirrored

YAGPDB.xyz BOT 3/15/2025 5:10 AM
Do you want to make a total conversion? Are you excited with an idea for a world, that you want to realise in CK3? And do you want to embark on that project with little prior modding experience? Consider these uncomfortable truths:
  • Total conversions are a terrifying chore to make. To get one going takes months of effort with little return on investment, and countless times where you're scratching your head at an inane vanilla system and spend a day in frustration before you figure it out. In that process, because you are figuring everything out, setbacks will happen again and again.
  • Total conversions are a big effort to maintain. If you've managed to finish one, after every big patch you will be redoing 10% of your mod again. Two or three times a year, you need to spend a few weeks on more dumb chores just to get the thing going as well as it did before the patch. And CK3 likely won't stop getting patches until the 2030s.
  • Total conversions do exist but they are, as a rule, made and maintained by teams. There are no TC mods in recent memory that have been made from scratch by a single person, and trust us, you don't want to be the first.
  • About every other week someone comes to the Coop with a vision for a world, and they ask for help making a map. They don't know what they are getting into, they burn themselves out and stop modding altogether.
Please, for your health and ours, consider very carefully whether you really want to do such a gigantic and thankless task as one of your first projects. CK3 is not a game engine, it is a game, and the larger the scope of your mod the bigger the pain.

Zockerhopper 3/29/2025 10:29 AM

xrstnfox 3/29/2025 10:30 AM
These values, specially raised army's position for both sea and land provinces, are used to define troop movement pathfinding. Be mindful that if there is any serious problem with a mod's locator files, errors.log should indicate that four files (generally holding buildings, raised army, army combat and siege weapon locator text files) have been created in the "[user][documents]\Paradox Interactive\Crusader Kings III\generated" folder. You can then copy those over to your mod's "[mod]/gfx/map/map_object_data/" folder, replace the old files and re-start the in-game map editor.

Kerbourgnec 4/19/2025 6:06 PM
I made a Gimp plugin to simplify province creation:
  • Link gimp to a province csv (either definitions.csv or another)
  • Generate a new color not already taken
  • Button to add a new province: prompted for name, [hidden: generates a new color, add the province with name and color to csv, ] > leaves the user with the new color to draw
  • Pick a color on the map -> Tells the name/id of the corresponding province (if it exists)
  • Pick a color on the map-> generate a new province in the csv (if it doesn't exist already) So it allows to create the whole province map in GIMP with reference maps overlays, and never need to check the csv at the same time / never need to copy paste colors
Can make it work with province maps already built/partially built Could add functionnalities if I need them / there is demand:
  • Reindex all provinces (by proximity)
  • More values when creating? (sea, ...)
  • Edit a large csv with terrain, culture, religion all in gimp (still possible to manually change them in excel later) and make the scripts to auto create the right files in the mod folder
  • others? Anyone interested?
 (edited)
6:07 PM
Just made it tonight, publishing tomorrow
Kerbourgnec
I made a Gimp plugin to simplify province creation:
  • Link gimp to a province csv (either definitions.csv or another)
  • Generate a new color not already taken
  • Button to add a new province: prompted for name, [hidden: generates a new color, add the province with name and color to csv, ] > leaves the user with the new color to draw
  • Pick a color on the map -> Tells the name/id of the corresponding province (if it exists)
  • Pick a color on the map-> generate a new province in the csv (if it doesn't exist already) So it allows to create the whole province map in GIMP with reference maps overlays, and never need to check the csv at the same time / never need to copy paste colors
Can make it work with province maps already built/partially built Could add functionnalities if I need them / there is demand:
  • Reindex all provinces (by proximity)
  • More values when creating? (sea, ...)
  • Edit a large csv with terrain, culture, religion all in gimp (still possible to manually change them in excel later) and make the scripts to auto create the right files in the mod folder
  • others? Anyone interested?

Kerbourgnec 4/21/2025 4:32 AM
Ok sp it seems I got if you followed like me: "If the river map refuses to export properly when using Gimp, close Gimp, copy the base game's river map into your mod folder, and then open it using Gimp. If prompted, ensure that the colour profile is retained (select keep) and ensure that the "Rendering Intent" is set to "Absolute colorimetric". This will reset any saved export settings that may be causing problems. Once you are done, choose "overwrite rivers.png" as your export option. " (from the wiki) On GIMP you also have to
  • Check Image/mode is Indexed
  • When saving, put Automatic instead of 8bpc
 (edited)
4:32 AM
then it worked for me

Ok sp it seems I got if you followed like me: "If the river map refuses to export properly when using Gimp, close Gimp, copy the base game's river map into your mod folder, and then open it using Gimp. This will reset any saved export settings that may be causing problems. Once you are done, choose "overwrite rivers.png" as your export option. " (from the wiki) On GIMP you also have to
  • Check Image/mode is Indexed

Hi! Is there a guide for CK3 Map edtiror? I'm struggling with placing cities, battles and sieges
MaxxxEC | Godherja 4/30/2025 8:59 PM
@Atlas4life no guide that i can link, but locators (the things that defines where cities/battles/units/sieges are placed) can be modified by the Map Object Editor tool in the mapeditor when you're in that tool, you press t as a hotkey to use the province selection tool click on the province you want to modify. then in the pane on the right itll say siege, army unit, holding, activity, and battle (or something along those lines) click on what you want to move, and then you can move it by using the move tool (hotkey is w), and rotate it with the rotate tool (hotkey e) if you don't see the locators in the province, but they show up in the pane, press f and it'll take you where they are, if they don't show up in the pane, either it's an impassable or the locators need to be generated for them, in which case the error log will tell you its generated locator files that you can replace your locator files with
MaxxxEC | Godherja

KeizerHarm | T4N 5/4/2025 3:17 PM
!tcmodding
YAGPDB.xyz BOT 5/4/2025 3:17 PM
Do you want to make a total conversion? Are you excited with an idea for a world, that you want to realise in CK3? And do you want to embark on that project with little prior modding experience? Consider these uncomfortable truths:
  • Total conversions are a terrifying chore to make. To get one going takes months of effort with little return on investment, and countless times where you're scratching your head at an inane vanilla system and spend a day in frustration before you figure it out. In that process, because you are figuring everything out, setbacks will happen again and again.
  • Total conversions are a big effort to maintain. If you've managed to finish one, after every big patch you will be redoing 10% of your mod again. Two or three times a year, you need to spend a few weeks on more dumb chores just to get the thing going as well as it did before the patch. And CK3 likely won't stop getting patches until the 2030s.
  • Total conversions do exist but they are, as a rule, made and maintained by teams. There are no TC mods in recent memory that have been made from scratch by a single person, and trust us, you don't want to be the first.
  • About every other week someone comes to the Coop with a vision for a world, and they ask for help making a map. They don't know what they are getting into, they burn themselves out and stop modding altogether.
Please, for your health and ours, consider very carefully whether you really want to do such a gigantic and thankless task as one of your first projects. CK3 is not a game engine, it is a game, and the larger the scope of your mod the bigger the pain.

R0B0 5/17/2025 9:12 AM
common/defines/graphic/00_graphics.txt PANNING_WIDTH # However far you want the player to be able to pan left to right. Panning to the edge would mean this is equal to map width PANNING_HEIGHT # However far you want the player to be able to pan up and down. Panning to the edge would mean this is equal to map height

Unknown Sage 5/29/2025 7:47 AM
hey everyone. I did a quick little analysis on the map image shown for All under Heaven. In an attempt to see what the new resolution would be with the expanded map size (for my own map modding work). And I figured I might just share this in case anyone else wanted to make use of this information. It seems pretty clear to me that the new map will have a resolution of 9216x4608 (Adding 1024 to the current width, and 512 to the current height for a total increase in pixels of 8912896). Which of course leaves the aspect ratio unchanged at 2:1. This is based on some lines I drew on the teaser image. Here is an image where I divided the map in blocks of 1024x1024 pixels with the red lines based on the current map. the blue are constructed lines for the part that is currently in the file but has no landmarks to compare to. and the purple outline is what I think the new map file edge would likely be. If I missed anything please let me know. (edited)
2
Unknown Sage 5/29/2025 8:00 AM
This is of course assuming they didn't shrink the existing map to fit everything on the 8192x4096 file. But it seems unlikely to me that they would have done that as it would be a lot more work probably to make sure everything still lines up nicely. (edited)
Splendid 5/29/2025 8:04 AM
I had thought it was just going into the blocked off section from the surround map.
Unknown Sage 5/29/2025 8:06 AM
yeah that would have been possible with a bit more extreme distortion on the eastern side. But since they added some parts south of the currently available africa provinces, they either have to expand the file resolution, or shrink the existing map. Because the southernmost provinces in africa are right on the edge of the 8192x4096 map. (edited)
Splendid 5/29/2025 8:07 AM
Oh yeah I forgot about Africa lol
Unknown Sage 5/29/2025 8:08 AM
expanding south and keeping the 2:1 aspect ratio does give some much needed breathing room to the east asia area as well. So it works out nicely to just increase the map file size.

Meriador 6/6/2025 1:24 AM
if anyone else finds themselves with a similar issue in the future: the problem was that a line in the defines file had gotten deleted; the game could still read the numbers fine, but the map editor tried to plug the gap in IDs by shifting things down, which is what moved things around. Apparently that doesn't crash the game!

Meriador 6/7/2025 4:16 AM
it doesn't need to be multiples of 1024. I know AtE's dimensions are both multiples of 256, but even that I'm not 100% confident is strictly necessary. The one restriction I do know is that the map can't be taller than it is wide.
4:18 AM

Hello, does anyone has a template for creating a map, i tried using the Atlantis template, but it just loads the normal ck3 map
BOMBUS_FRIGIDUS | TWR 6/17/2025 5:44 PM
Hi! There is not a current map template to my knowledge. The Atlantis template omits graphic files because, from my experience, developing map graphics is really a matter of personal taste and TC goals; I believe it's best for a TC developer to work through the details from scratch. That forces the developer to learn what each files does, and that helps to avoid omitting effects (e.g. that of the color map) out of ignorance. I'd suggest looking at vanilla and existing TCs to see which files do what, then picking groups of map files to edit for your purposes.

YAGPDB.xyz BOT 8/8/2025 11:32 AM
Do you want to make a total conversion? Are you excited with an idea for a world, that you want to realise in CK3? And do you want to embark on that project with little prior modding experience? Consider these uncomfortable truths:
  • Total conversions are a terrifying chore to make. To get one going takes months of effort with little return on investment, and countless times where you're scratching your head at an inane vanilla system and spend a day in frustration before you figure it out. In that process, because you are figuring everything out, setbacks will happen again and again.
  • Total conversions are a big effort to maintain. If you've managed to finish one, after every big patch you will be redoing 10% of your mod again. Two or three times a year, you need to spend a few weeks on more dumb chores just to get the thing going as well as it did before the patch. And CK3 likely won't stop getting patches until the 2030s.
  • Total conversions do exist but they are, as a rule, made and maintained by teams. There are no TC mods in recent memory that have been made from scratch by a single person, and trust us, you don't want to be the first.
  • About every other week someone comes to the Coop with a vision for a world, and they ask for help making a map. They don't know what they are getting into, they burn themselves out and stop modding altogether.
Please, for your health and ours, consider very carefully whether you really want to do such a gigantic and thankless task as one of your first projects. CK3 is not a game engine, it is a game, and the larger the scope of your mod the bigger the pain.

KeizerHarm | T4N 8/12/2025 10:15 AM
KeizerHarm | T4N 8/12/2025 10:23 AM
I think, the most likely scenario is that the maps will load just fine with AUH but work will be required to make use of the new approach to height and the biome masks. An alternate scenario is that existing height maps will simply not work and/or that more extensive rework to textures is necessary to get them to show up borderline acceptably. There's also a possibility that the new features have a new underlying assumption and all of us who took the bold step to make a map with different dimensions than vanilla will face crashes and we're left scratching our heads and begging the devs to get stuff fixed before being remotely able to launch, let alone release an update.
BOMBUS_FRIGIDUS | TWR 8/12/2025 12:13 PM
The changes Lundh wrote up are almost all specific to PDX's workflow outside of CK3, so I don't think the dev diary shows any changes that would break mod maps. But I would be surprised if there aren't some boring changes to files or file structures that end up breaking mod maps. (edited)
BOMBUS_FRIGIDUS | TWR
The changes Lundh wrote up are almost all specific to PDX's workflow outside of CK3, so I don't think the dev diary shows any changes that would break mod maps. But I would be surprised if there aren't some boring changes to files or file structures that end up breaking mod maps. (edited)
plundh 8/12/2025 2:32 PM

To properly understand, the masks are [heightmap (the previous topology you used), which is the actual Earth heightmap; navigable lakes and rivers; rivers; oceans; lakes)] The resulting heightmap is one with exageraged erosion features to look good at this scale. Am I mistaken or are the trees not taken into account here? I would assume another "tree density" input, and it is split into different maps through the biome feature. plundh 8/23/2025 9:12 AM
trees are still are still a mix of manual and procedural. we don't really have enough diversity in foliage at the moment to warrant a more complicated system, though I would love to add more variety there in the future. we do some rough scattering in photoshop based on terrain types, mix in some of the generated output from gaea and then adjust it by hand in the in-game editor to make it look more natural. it's not a very sophisticated process at the moment. in other words, we don't do anything biome-specific fro the vegetation
Kerbourgnec 8/23/2025 11:36 AM
Thank you!

Splendid 8/27/2025 5:31 AM
Yeah make a mod that copies the file structure for the holdings so: gfx>map>map_object_data and place the vanilla file "building_locators" in there Then open the game with the mod active with the map editor using "-mapeditor" as a launch option in steam
5:35 AM
Once the game loads into the editor you can go the locators section (In the left side of the screen) and you can select the baronies you want to edit by clicking on them in the map. Once you select the barony you want to edit you can select the holding graphic and move it around wherever you want (even outside the borders of the barony) then you can hit save/save all and you'll be done.

KeizerHarm | T4N 10/27/2025 5:30 PM
This is a very interesting project... The difficulty would depend greatly on how much you want to recreate. On a basic level you could, with some work, start with the heightmap (Blender has a displacement modifier that'll take a bitmap as input); then import the terrain masks one by one to build up the visual look. You'll need to rebuild shaders, and then the ocean will be one major challenge as that is animated and affected by various textures determining the directions of the waves and such. Then loading in rivers will I think be basically impossible unless you rebuild part of the game, same goes for on-map models like trees, holdings (edited)
1
5:32 PM
By the way that work would all be about transporting an existing map to some external software like Blender. Actually creating the map would have to be done in the map editor, and getting a map to look nice there takes hours upon hours of careful sculpting.
1
5:34 PM
I'll let others chime in if they have ideas, but I think this would be pretty complicated. I think CK3 might not be the right place to start but I'm not knowledgeable enough to tell for sure
1

physicsprogrammer 10/29/2025 5:30 PM
if you mean paint and then fill out definition file from that, there's one in #🤝shared-resources i think...?
5:32 PM
if you mean fill out definition file with a bunch of pre-generated colours, this python script should do the trick to generate 255 province ids
start_num = 1 quantity = 254 # change the following to change which color is generated red_channel = 1 green_channel = 0 blue_channel = 0 with open('definition.csv','w') as file: for num in range(start_num, start_num + quantity): red = red_channel*num green = green_channel*num blue = blue_channel*num file.write(str(num) + ';' + str(red) + ';' + str(green) + ';' + str(blue) + ';' + str(num) + ';x;') file.write('\n')
 (edited)
1
5:32 PM
(then you can paint them on in the map editor)

ck2rpg 11/3/2025 12:18 PM
I might have missed some of my changes because I was not too diligent on tracking, but here is a running list of things I updated to get my map generator working again after AUH if anyone needs it (not sure which among these would crash without update): (1) common/defines (for WORLD_EXTENTS if not AUH dimensions) and heightmap.heightmap (original_heightmap_size) need to match your dimensions if you were relying on default before and hadn't done so already (2) add tree_sakura_01_mask, tree_sakura_02_mask, tree_sakura_03_mask, and tree_sakura_forest_mask to content_source/map_objects/masks (3) Terrain masks are now moved to gfx/map/terrain/masks and gfx/map/terrain/masks_gen. (4) All 52 masks in masks_gen are new and need to be appropriately sized (full dimensions). You could do this quickly with a python script and gimp if that is your cup of tea. (5) There are now 70 masks in gfx/map/terrain/masks. I think this is a list of changes - tried to compare against some old maps: (a) New: _debug_mask, central_lowlands_02_mask, central_lowlands_03_mask, central_mountain mask, drought_cracks_mask, drought_mask, farm_paddy_01_mask, flood_mask, plains_01_dry_mud_mask, summer_grass_mask (b) Gone: coastline_cliff_brown_mask, forestfloor_02_mask, medi_grass_02_mask, medi_hills_01_mask, plains_01_desat_mask, (c) Modified name: mountain_02_desert_mask is now mountain_02_desert_mask_old

ck2rpg 11/7/2025 8:42 PM
Was it working before AUH?
ck2rpg
I might have missed some of my changes because I was not too diligent on tracking, but here is a running list of things I updated to get my map generator working again after AUH if anyone needs it (not sure which among these would crash without update): (1) common/defines (for WORLD_EXTENTS if not AUH dimensions) and heightmap.heightmap (original_heightmap_size) need to match your dimensions if you were relying on default before and hadn't done so already (2) add tree_sakura_01_mask, tree_sakura_02_mask, tree_sakura_03_mask, and tree_sakura_forest_mask to content_source/map_objects/masks (3) Terrain masks are now moved to gfx/map/terrain/masks and gfx/map/terrain/masks_gen. (4) All 52 masks in masks_gen are new and need to be appropriately sized (full dimensions). You could do this quickly with a python script and gimp if that is your cup of tea. (5) There are now 70 masks in gfx/map/terrain/masks. I think this is a list of changes - tried to compare against some old maps: (a) New: _debug_mask, central_lowlands_02_mask, central_lowlands_03_mask, central_mountain mask, drought_cracks_mask, drought_mask, farm_paddy_01_mask, flood_mask, plains_01_dry_mud_mask, summer_grass_mask (b) Gone: coastline_cliff_brown_mask, forestfloor_02_mask, medi_grass_02_mask, medi_hills_01_mask, plains_01_desat_mask, (c) Modified name: mountain_02_desert_mask is now mountain_02_desert_mask_old

ÁÉàÂ≠ê íãß 11/15/2025 9:26 PM
there are so many numbers in the files of map_object_data, what do they mean
Licarious | MoreNavigableRrivers 11/15/2025 9:54 PM
there are 2 different types of files in map_object_data. game_object_locator cover things that provinces have like units, city, and fort objects. The numbers in there should be fairly self explanatory by the scopes they are encapsulated in. object cover the non province things like animals, lakes, and bridge objects. These have walls or numbers that more difficult to parse at a glance. the order goes something like positonX positonY positonZ positonW(?) Rotation1 Rotation2 Rotation3 ScaleX ScaleY ScaleZ. Unless you are developing scripts to modify these files then you should not be concerned with them and just alter the objects in the map editor. (edited)
Licarious | MoreNavigableRrivers
there are 2 different types of files in map_object_data. game_object_locator cover things that provinces have like units, city, and fort objects. The numbers in there should be fairly self explanatory by the scopes they are encapsulated in. object cover the non province things like animals, lakes, and bridge objects. These have walls or numbers that more difficult to parse at a glance. the order goes something like positonX positonY positonZ positonW(?) Rotation1 Rotation2 Rotation3 ScaleX ScaleY ScaleZ. Unless you are developing scripts to modify these files then you should not be concerned with them and just alter the objects in the map editor. (edited)
